<font color="#FF0000">FOR HONOR AND FOR HER</font><br>
<tt>Tue Feb 18 21:02:34 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
A few years back I went to see a grade school teacher, Mrs. Wardell in Salem, Oregon.  During our discussions, I found out that her husband had been killed returning from a bombing raid over Germany during WW II.  There was an Eighth Air Force reunion in England, which she had attended.  She brought home a flier from the earlier era, which had a poem on it.  I took the poemm home, wrote it out, then added my own post script.  I made it into my own sheet, which I'll send to anyone who e-mails me a request.  Here's the result without the graphics:<br><br>
For Honor and For Her<br><br>
Somewhere a woman, thrusting fear away,<br>
Faces the future bravely for your sake;<br>
Toils on from dawn till dark, from day to day;<br>
Fights back her tears, nor heeds the bitter ache;<br>
She loves you, trusts you, breaths in prayer your name; <br>
Soil not her faith in you by sin or shame.<br><br>
Somewhere a woman watches--filled with pride;<br>
Shrined inher heart, you share a place with none;<br>
She toils, she waits, she prays, 'till side by side<br>
You stand together when the battle's done.<br>
Oh keep for her dear sake a shameless name;<br>
Bring back to her a manhood free from shame.<br><br>
--M. Scruton<br>
From the Morning Worship Service<br>
Rev. Dolman, Rector<br>
Church of England<br>
Sunday, August 22, 1943<br><br>
A Post Script<br>
by John C. Ratliff, August 7, 1992<br><br>
I have seen war, some twenty-seven years later,<br>
After this poem had been lost to our services.<br>
Oh, how I wish some of my fellow servicemen<br>
Could have seen it, felt it, been shamed by it.<br><br>
Our war was different in many ways,<br>
A country far away, a culture so vastly different;<br>
A political climate which seemed to state<br>
That we were the bad guys, not they.<br><br>
But there were some of us who knew,<br>
The difference between responsibility<br>
And the same word with an &quot;ir&quot; prefix;<br>
Who knew that no matter what happened, we still lived<br>
ultimately with ourselves.<br><br>
So let us hope that this poem can form a base, where again<br>
service people will know <br>
That they are not alone, that people still love them, <br>
and that they have honor, and duty<br>
To fulfill, so that our country can continue to shine the <br>
light of freedom to other peoples.
